sols_latex:
We write \emph{H} as a sum of \emph{F} and \emph{G}:

\begin{align*}
H(x,y) = \int_y^0 \ln(2 + \sin t) dt + \int_0^x \ln(2 + \sin t) dt = G(y) + F(x).
\end{align*}

Then

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle H_x = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(F(x)+G(y)) = F'(x) + 0 = \ln(2+\sin(x))
\end{align*}
and similarly

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle H_y = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(F(x)+G(y)) = 0 + G'(y) = -\ln(2+\sin(y))
\end{align*}
where we used the knowledge about the derivatives \emph{F'(x)} and
\emph{G'(y)} from
{part
(a)}. Finally, all that is left to do is to plug in the given values to
find that

\begin{align*}
\nabla H\left(\frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}\right) = \left\langle F'\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right), G'\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) \right\rangle = \langle \ln 3, -\ln 3\rangle
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Now define

\begin{align*}
H(x,y) = \int_y^x \ln(2+\sin t)\,dt.
\end{align*}

Find the first partial derivatives of \emph{H} and use this to compute
